Given your example the point of moving the implementation &quot;up&quot; on the layers would be to be able to use the same timer component in different parts of your app where maybe the start() should behave differently each time.
The component itself would have no way to know what each specific &quot;start&quot; event should do, since the component should not have any knowledge of how it is been used at any time.

Think of the callbacks as event handlers, where the caller passes down what should be done when an event occurs

This actually enforces DRY, since you need 1 timer ( the logic of start,pause,stop,&quot;timer reached&quot; maybe etc) and then each caller hooks up what he wants to do when those events occur.

If you think of the structure of React itself, and its life cycle event, its the same thing. &quot;ComponentDidMount&quot; is no different than you timer&#39;s &quot;start&quot; for example, just a different context. The concept thought is the same

EDIT: It is important to think about what stays fixed in your component for everyone and what should be configurable.
Your timer for example will always tick once per second, right? So the time tracking part will always be constant for your app, it should reside within the component. The component should have a Start,Pause,Stop set of methods defined in it, since stop will always just stop the count, start will always resume it. 
But you will need to expose an OnStart,OnStop,OnPause, so that callers can hook the logic they need using your timer. I dont know if i can explain this well enough...

EDIT 2:
For example check below for the Start method of the timer:

   

     function Start(){
        // set the interval here or wtver way you will have to measure ticks
    // ...
    // ...
        if(this.props.OnStart)
         this.props.OnStart();
        }

Now ofcourse the callers will not be responsible for implementing the actual ticking ( allthough one day someone may come and request a tracker that is relative to someone travelling the speed of light or something, so the ticking can also be configurable...), but if they do need to have a hook on the start event, and they will, then you can implement it this way.
What the callback function does is not known to the component ( business logic moved up) but the common-to-all &#39;tick once per second&#39; now is no concern to the callers

EDIT 3:
Ok so.. if the button is clicked we will start the timer and then call any hooks given by the props

   

     function OnEveryClick(){
        // here you will write anything you want your component to do every time the button is clicked, regardless of who is the caller, like our previous Start method
    this.Start();
        }

    function ButtonClicked(){
    // first you call your method every time
     this.OnEveryClick();
    // then if the caller also wants to do some stuff, you evaluate their function aswell
      if(this.props.OnSubmit)
        this.props.OnSubmit();
    }

Then on the render you do something like this 

    &lt;button onClick={this.ButtonClicked.bind(this)}&gt;

