You could update your pattern to match any char except a whitespace character or a `/` using a [negated character class](https://www.regular-expressions.info/charclass.html#negated). Your pattern currently matches 1+ digits only.

Note that if you want to use the `/` as a delimiter, you have to add it to the start as wel and escape the forward slashes inside the pattern.

[Regex demo](https://regex101.com/r/MTRTI7/1) | [Php demo](https://3v4l.org/IBbke)

    $url=&quot;https://example.com/search/node/Star/loc=9&quot;;
    preg_match(&#39;/search\/node\/\K[^\s\/]+/&#39;, $url,$m);
    $KEYWORD=  $m[0];
    echo $KEYWORD;

Output

    Star

If you would use a different delimiter you code might look like

    preg_match(&#39;~search/node/\K[^\s/]+~&#39;, $url,$m);

You can put parenthesis around what you want to capture : the first group will be available in `$m[1]` :

    $url=&quot;https://example.com/search/node/KEYWORD3/loc=9&quot;;
    preg_match(&#39;|search/node/([^/]+)/?|&#39;, $url,$m);
    $KEYWORD=  $m[1]; // KEYWORD3

